The paper deals with reinforcement learning algorithms, specifically policy optimization methods, which are commonly studied in the machine learning community. The paper proposes a new algorithm and analyzes its performance in a finite-horizon MDP setting with unknown transitions and bandit feedback. This falls under the category of machine learning (cs.LG) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The paper also involves optimization and regret analysis, which are relevant to the categories of data structures and algorithms (cs.DS) and multi-agent systems (cs.MA). Finally, the paper deals with decision-making in a dynamic environment, which is relevant to the category of robotics (cs.RO).
